				<td colspan="2"><span>I love /melody.  I use it all the time, and I am a d*mn fine bard.
<br />

<br />
Twisting is a function of computer speed, connection speed, and a moderate degree of attention.  It is NOT the defining characteristic of a good bard.  As many have said, a monkey can twist just fine.
<br />

<br />
A good bard is a excellent puller.../melody application for pulling? Zero that I can find.
<br />

<br />
A good bard is a fast, aware mezzer.  /melody appilcation? Zero.  Twisting aid will not help me notice a loose mob and lock it down.
<br />

<br />
What is melody for? 20min raid fights where you will be twisting PoV, PC, and Chorus of Life non-stop and you may not stop to mez or whatever because the AE's are gonna eat your clerics if you do.     It is fine for the beatdown once you have your single pull tanked and controlled in groups.  It is a dream for kiting.
<br />

<br />
The biggest problem of using /melody is getting used to the command and it's quirks.  Must have a /melody off button...use it frequently.  Understand that when note is missed you don't have to restart with /melody key...just tap the song you want to start with.../melody will pick up from there.
<br />

<br />
If you think /melody has ruined bards, I dont think you had very good criteria for determining who is a good bard.  I am a hard-core player...I raid 7 days a week and am online at least 6 hours a day, everyday.  Before /melody I was having chronic wrist pain that prevented me from playing EQ outside raid times.  Plane of Time was dreaded due to the pain it would cause.  Now I can play all day without any pain at the end of the night.  
<br />

<br />
I love /melody.  You go ahead and skip using it...I hope your body is stronger than mine - but you will not be a better bard for your pain.</span></td>
